{"key":"processedPost-12698655","value":{"id":12698655,"first":12698337,"last":12698655,"when":1275869369,"utime":"06/07/10 03:09 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>insipidtoast said:</strong><br />I know standard procedure for sterilizing is to bring PC up to 15 psi, let stay at high for 5 min, then switch the stove down to low.</blockquote><br />No.<br />Put the stove on high with no weight on the nozzle.&nbsp; It should be open to vent for five to ten minutes worth of steam escaping.&nbsp; After that, put the weight on and once 15 psi is reached it will begin to jiggle.&nbsp; At this point, turn down the burner to the point where it rattles no more than a few times per minute.&nbsp; If it rattles more than that, you're losing water from the PC, but also from the moisture within your jars.&nbsp; I use a gauge and turn the stove to the lowest setting that will maintain 14 psi, therefore NO rattling of the weight.&nbsp;  <br />Since you don't have a gauge, you'll have to let the weight rattle a few times per minute, but more than that risks it running dry, or drying out your substrates.<br />RR"}}